# Socrepho Web - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is a simple, professional website for Socrepho - a mobile app development company.
Technology: Vanilla HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript (no frameworks)

---

## File Structure Rules

### Directory Organization
```
socrpeho_web/
├── index.html          # Main HTML file
├── css/
│   └── styles.css      # All styles (single file)
├── js/
│   └── main.js         # All JavaScript (single file)
├── assets/
│   └── images/         # Image files
├── .cursorrules        # This file
└── README.md           # Documentation
```

### Naming Conventions
- Files: `kebab-case.ext` (e.g., `about-page.html`)
- CSS classes: `kebab-case` (e.g., `.hero-title`)
- JS variables/functions: `camelCase` (e.g., `handleScroll`)
- CSS variables: `--kebab-case` (e.g., `--color-primary`)

---

## HTML Rules

1. Use semantic HTML5 elements (`<nav>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<footer>`)
2. Always include `lang="en"` attribute on `<html>`
3. Include meta viewport for responsive design
4. Keep structure simple and readable
5. Use meaningful class names that describe purpose

---

## CSS Rules

### Organization
1. CSS variables are defined in `:root` at the top
2. Sections are organized with comment headers
3. Mobile-first or desktop-first (currently desktop-first)

### Best Practices
1. Use CSS variables for colors, spacing, typography
2. Use `rem` for font sizes, `px` for borders/shadows
3. Keep specificity low - avoid deep nesting
4. Group related properties together

### Section Order in CSS:
1. Variables (`:root`)
2. Reset & Base styles
3. Layout (Container, Grid)
4. Components (Navbar, Buttons, Cards)
5. Sections (Hero, Services, Work, About, Contact, Footer)
6. Animations
7. Responsive (Media Queries at bottom)

---

## JavaScript Rules

1. Keep JavaScript minimal - only for necessary interactivity
2. Use `const` and `let`, never `var`
3. Use modern ES6+ syntax (arrow functions, template literals)
4. Add comments for each major section/function
5. Wrap in `DOMContentLoaded` event listener

---

## Markdown/Documentation Rules

### README.md
- Keep documentation concise and practical
- Include file structure diagram
- Document how to run/preview the site
- List any dependencies or requirements

### Comments
- HTML: Use `<!-- Comment -->` for section markers
- CSS: Use `/* Comment */` for section headers
- JS: Use `//` for single line, `/* */` for multi-line

---

